A function is its own inverse if it reflects across the line $y=x$. Since the line $y=x$ has the same slope as the tangent line to $x^2-6x+12$ at $x=3$ (where the case changes), we know that the function is symmetric across this tangent line, giving the formula \[\left|x-\text{real root}\right|=\left|f(x)-f(\text{real root})\right|\]where they are equal if $x$ is on the same side as the root where the function is subtracted by the root, and not equal if on the other side. The real root of $x^2-6x+12=0$ is at $x=3\pm i$, where we just take the real part $x=3$ as the line of reflection. The value of the function at the root is $3^2-6\cdot3+12=3$, so the case after $x=3$ will start there. The tangent line to the function at $x=3$ is $f(3)+(x-3)f'(3)=3-2(x-3)=7-2x$, which gives a reflected point of $7-x$ using the formula we stated above. Therefore, the function $k(x)$ is $\boxed{7-x}$.

