Let $d$ be the common difference in the arithmetic sequence. The four angles then have measures $129^\circ - 3d,$ $129^\circ - 2d,$ $129^\circ - d,$ and $129^\circ,$ in some order. The sum of the angle measures of a quadrilateral is $360^\circ,$ so $ 129^\circ + (129^\circ - d) + (129^\circ - 2d) + (129^\circ - 3d) = 360^\circ.$ Simplifying the left side gives $516^\circ - 6d = 360^\circ,$ so $d = \frac{516^\circ - 360^\circ}{6} = 26^\circ.$ Therefore, the second largest angle has measure $129^\circ - d = \boxed{103^\circ}.$

