The slopes of the lines will be equal if the lines are parallel. The slope for the first line is $3a+2$, and the slope for the second line is $\dfrac{a-4}{2}$ (since we must divide by $2$ to rewrite the equation in the form $y=mx+b$). Setting these two slopes equal and solving for $a$ gives \begin{align*}
3a+2&=\frac{a-4}{2}\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 6a+4&=a-4\\
\Rightarrow\qquad 5a&=-8\\
\Rightarrow\qquad a&=\boxed{-\frac{8}{5}}.
\end{align*}

We can start by finding the x-intercepts of the graph, by setting $f(x) = 0$ and solving for $x$. This gives us: \begin{align*}
\frac{(x-2)^2-9}{3} &= 0 \\
\Rightarrow \qquad (x-2)^2 - 9 &= 0\\
\Rightarrow \qquad (x-2-3)(x-2+3) &= 0\\
\Rightarrow \qquad (x-5)(x+1) &= 0
\end{align*}So the zeros are located at $x = 5$ and $x = -1$. We can then find the $y$-intercept of the graph by setting $x = 0$ and solving for $y = f(0)$. This gives us: \begin{align*}
f(0) &= \frac{(0-2)^2-9}{3} \\
\Rightarrow \qquad f(0) &= \frac{4-9}{3}\\
\Rightarrow \qquad f(0) &= -\frac{5}{3}
\end{align*}Together, these points form a right triangle with a base of 6 units and a height of $\frac{5}{3}$ units. So, the area of the polygon is $\frac{1}{2}bh = \frac{1}{2}(6)\left(\frac{5}{3}\right)=\boxed{5}$.

