First, we can translate the equation $5y=2x$ into slope-intercept form ($y = mx+b$), to get the equation $y = \dfrac{2}{5}x$. We substitute this equation into the equation $3x - 4y = 7$ to get \begin{align*} 3x - 4\left(\frac{2}{5}x\right) &= 7
\\\Rightarrow\qquad 11x &= 35
\\\Rightarrow\qquad x &= \frac{35}{11}
\end{align*}

Then we can substitute $x=\frac{35}{11}$ into the equation $y=\frac{2}{5}x$, which gets $y = \frac{14}{11}$. Therefore, the point $Z$ is $\left(\frac{35}{11}, \frac{14}{11} \right)$, so the sum of coordinates of point $Z$ is $\frac{35}{11}+ \frac{14}{11}=\boxed{\frac{49}{11}}$.

The shortest distance from a point to a line is along a line perpendicular to the given line. The slope of the line $y = 2x - 2$ is 2, so the slope of the line through $A$ that is perpendicular to the given line is $-1/2$. The $y$-intercept of that line is the $y$-coordinate (which is 0 in this case) of $A$ plus the opposite of the slope times the $x$-coordinate of $A$. Thus, that line has an equation of $y = -\frac{1}{2}x + 3$. These two lines intersect at the point given by $-\frac{1}{2}x + 3 = 2x - 2$, which is $x = 5/3$. That corresponds to a point of $\left(\frac{5}{3}, \frac{4}{3}\right)$. Therefore, the shortest distance from $A$ to the original line is  \[\sqrt{\left(6-\frac{5}{3}\right)^2+\left(0-\frac{4}{3}\right)^2} = \boxed{2 \sqrt{7}}.\]

