The domain of a function is the set of all possible x-values. For this function, the denominator cannot be equal to 0 and cannot be negative, because you can't take the square root of a negative number. 

The denominator is equal to 0 when $x^2 -5x + 6=0$. This quadratic equation factors to be $(x-2)(x-3)=0$. Thus, the denominator is zero when $x = 2$ or $x = 3$. 

Therefore, these values must be excluded from the domain. The set of all other real numbers is the solution to $x^2-5x+6 > 0$. The quadratic factors to $(x-2)(x-3)$, and the product of two numbers is positive if and only if the two numbers are either both positive or both negative.

If $x < 2$, then $x-2$ and $x-3$ are both negative, so $(x-2)(x-3) > 0$.

If $2 < x < 3$, then $x-2 > 0$ and $x-3 < 0$, so $(x-2)(x-3) < 0$.

If $x > 3$, then $x-2$ and $x-3$ are both positive, so $(x-2)(x-3) > 0$.

Therefore, the solution to $(x-2)(x-3) < 0$ is $2 < x < 3$, so the solution to $x^2-5x+6 > 0$ is $(-\infty,2) \cup (3, \infty)$, and the domain of the function is $\boxed{(-\infty,2) \cup (3, \infty)}$.
